<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: PORT HUENEME; NAVY TO CHARGE 3 IN CAPTURE OF 
DESERTER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JULIE FIELDS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Three members of the U.S. Navy's military police in Port Hueneme are facing 
charges of misconduct for apprehending a deserter off base without 
authorization, investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
 The three men, in addition to a civilian employee of the military police at 
the Naval Construction Battalion Center, captured the deserter by stopping him 
while he was driving in Oxnard Nov. 16 , Navy officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 William Nugent, resident agent in charge of the Naval Criminal Investigative 
Service in Port Hueneme, said the four were outside their jurisdiction when 
they made the stop and did not have the authority to do so. "Their jurisdiction 
is within the base," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 The deserter, whom military officials would not identify, was already facing 
military charges when he left the base, Nugent said.  
</P>
<P>
 Master-at-Arms Senior Chief George R. Taylor, Operations Specialist 2nd Class 
Mark A. Bassett and Signalman 2nd Class Thomas S. Hinson have all opted to have 
their case tried during a court martial, rather than settling the charges 
against them in an administrative hearing. 
</P>
<P>
 If found guilty of a charge of dereliction of duty, the three could face up to 
six months in confinement and a bad conduct discharge, Nugent said. 
</P>
<P>
 A base spokeswoman said that a date for the court martial has not yet been 
set. 
</P>
<P>
 Byron J. Frank, a civilian employee of the military police who was allegedly 
involved in the incident, will probably face disciplinary procedures, Nugent 
said. JULIE FIELDS 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020194-0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 009062 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
February 1, 1994, Tuesday, Ventura West Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 2; Column 4; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
225 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: 5TH SUSPECT HELD IN SLAYING AT MOTEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JULIE FIELDS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Police have arrested a fifth suspect in connection with the fatal shooting of 
a Whittier man at a Ventura motel in December, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 Alfonso Serrato Cortez, 21, was taken into custody Thursday and booked into 
County Jail on suspicion of acting as an accessory to the Dec. 18 murder of 
21-year-old Paul Martinez at the Motel 6 on Johnson Drive, police said. 
</P>
<P>
 Cortez, of Port Hueneme, was released on $5,000 bail and is expected to be 
charged by the district attorney's office on Thursday, said Deputy Dist. Atty. 
Matthew J. Hardy, who is handling the case. 
</P>
<P>
 Three other suspects were charged with murder last Thursday, and a woman was 
charged with being an accessory to the crime for trying to help cover up the 
slaying, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
 All three murder suspects are being held in jail in lieu of $1 million bail, 
and the woman is being held on $250,000 bail, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
 Martinez went to Motel 6 the night of the shooting with a friend from Los 
Angeles and a group of people from Santa Paula, police said. The shooting 
occurred after an encounter with a group of people from Oxnard and Port Hueneme 
that included gang members. 
</P>
<P>
 Authorities have said that at least two gunmen opened fire from inside their 
cars in the motel's parking lot. Martinez was shot and killed as he stood on 
the second-story walkway. JULIE FIELDS 
</P>
</TEXT>
