<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: ISLAMABAD; SEPARATIST SUPPORT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Across Pakistan on Saturday, shops should remain shuttered and bazaars eerily 
silent as the country observes a government-endorsed general strike to show 
solidarity with the people of Kashmir.  
</P>
<P>
 Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto has swung her support behind the action, 
originally called by an all-party parliamentary committee in support of 
militants waging a separatist campaign in India's only Muslim-majority 
state.But the stakes don't just concern Kashmir.  
</P>
<P>
 Bhutto's image has taken a beating lately due to a messy political feud with 
her family. Opposition leader Nawaz Sharif, who came out earlier for the 
strike, accuses her of not uttering a single word in defense of the Kashmiris. 
By calling on Pakistanis to stay away from work for a day, Bhutto is trying to 
keep from being outflanked on a hot-button issue by her enemies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
