<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; OHIO; HYATT BEGINS BID FOR METZENBAUM'S SEAT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Democrat Joel Hyatt began his U.S. Senate campaign, undaunted that he could be 
hurt by the movie "Philadelphia," which has brought attention to his firm's 
firing of an AIDS-infected lawyer.Hyatt is seeking to replace his 
father-in-law, Democratic Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum, who is retiring. The film 
was inspired by dozens of cases, including one involving Hyatt's firm, the 
film's publicist said. Clarence Cain, a senior attorney with Hyatt Legal 
Services in Philadelphia, was fired seven years ago after he learned he had 
AIDS. He sued for discrimination and won $157,000 in 1990. He died two months 
later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020194-0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 009185 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
February 1, 1994, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part A; Page 13; Column 2; National Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
73 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; NATIONWIDE; SEVERE COLD GRIPS MUCH OF THE U.S. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Temperatures plummeted to record lows in the Upper Midwest from a new surge of 
arctic air.Subzero temperatures were common overnight from the Great Basin and 
the Rockies across the northern Plains and the Great Lakes. Lows were in the 
20s and 30s below zero from the Upper Mississippi Valley to northern New 
England. Temperatures fell to the freezing point as far south as the Gulf Coast 
states, the National Weather Service said. 
</P>
