<TEXT>
<P>
 Rates Rise on T-Bills: The Treasury Department sold $12.6 billion of new 
three-month bills at an average discount rate of 2.99%, up from 2.96% last 
week. Another $12.6 billion of new six-month bills was sold at an average 
discount rate of 3.16%, up from 3.14% last week.The three-month bill rate was 
the highest since they sold for 3.02% on Jan. 10. The six-month bill rate was 
the highest since they averaged 3.18%, also on Jan. 10. The new discount rates 
understate the actual return to investors -- 3.06% for three-month bills with a 
$10,000 bill selling for $9,924.40 and 3.26% for a six-month bill selling for 
$9,840.20. The discount rate reflects the price discount received when 
government securities are purchased at less than face value. T-Bill Auction: 
</P>
<P>
 6-month: 3.16% 
</P>
<P>
 3-month: 2.99% 
</P>
</TEXT>
