<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: MOSCOW; THE 'NEAR ABROAD' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Russian President Boris N. Yeltsin is scheduled to visit Georgia on Wednesday 
in his first trip to a former Soviet republic since the Dec. 12 Russian 
parliamentary election. 
</P>
<P>
 Georgian leader Eduard A. Shevardnadze said the visit "will signify the 
recognition of Georgia's independence," but Yeltsin's conduct will be 
scrutinized for clues about Russia's new policy toward the nations of the "near 
abroad." 
</P>
<P>
 Russia has supplied troops to help Shevardnadze put down an armed rebellion, 
and Georgia has joined the Russian-led Commonwealth of Independent States. The 
leaders will sign agreements on friendship, free trade and economic 
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
