<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: COSTA MESA; EX-MWD DIRECTOR SENTENCED TO PRISON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LEN HALL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A former Orange County director of the Metropolitan Water District of Southern 
California was sentenced Monday to three months in prison and fined $10,000 for 
federal income tax evasion. 
</P>
<P>
 Carl J. Kymla of Costa Mesa, a 20-year member of the MWD board and a former 
city councilman in Newport Beach, also must spend three months in a community 
confinement center during a three-year period of supervised release, according 
to the sentence handed down by U.S. District Judge Terry J. Hatter Jr. 
</P>
<P>
 Kymla is scheduled to turn himself in to begin his sentence March 14, said 
Assistant U.S. Atty. Kimberly Dunne. 
</P>
<P>
 Neither Kymla nor his attorney, Paul Raymond, returned phone calls for comment 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 Kymla, who runs Newport Beach-based Municipal Services Consultant Inc., 
pleaded guilty last October to one count of failing to report approximately 
$75,000 of income on his 1987 tax return, Dunne said. He also admitted failing 
to report approximately $140,000 in income in 1986, Dunne said. 
</P>
<P>
 Although he faced a maximum of 10 years in prison and a $500,000 fine after 
being indicted in 1993 on two counts of tax evasion, "as part of a plea 
agreement, the government moved to dismiss one count," Dunne said. 
</P>
<P>
 Kymla resigned from his seat on the 51-member MWD board last October just 
before entering his guilty plea. He served on the board as a director appointed 
by the Municipal Water District of Orange County. 
</P>
<P>
 As an MWD director, Kymla had been chairman of the special budget committee 
since its inception in 1976. The committee had the final word on MWD's 
$820-million budget. 
</P>
<P>
 In 1978, Kymla was the general manager of the Moulton Niguel Water District in 
Laguna Niguel and one of five district officials indicted on felony charges of 
misappropriating district property, including using district equipment and 
employees to handle chores around his home. 
</P>
<P>
 At the time, prosecutors admitted that their evidence against Kymla was weak 
and charges were dismissed against him in February, 1979. He retired from the 
district post one day later.LEN HALL 
</P>
</TEXT>
