<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; OHIO; HYATT BEGINS BID FOR METZENBAUM'S SEAT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Democrat Joel Hyatt began his U.S. Senate campaign, undaunted that he could be 
hurt by the movie "Philadelphia," which has brought attention to his firm's 
firing of an AIDS-infected lawyer.Hyatt is seeking to replace his 
father-in-law, Democratic Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum, who is retiring. The film 
was inspired by dozens of cases, including one involving Hyatt's firm, the 
film's publicist said. Clarence Cain, a senior attorney with Hyatt Legal 
Services in Philadelphia, was fired seven years ago after he learned he had 
AIDS. He sued for discrimination and won $157,000 in 1990. He died two months 
later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
